&nbsp;
To further complicate things, for the majority, a new fact could be involved, of which politics will certainly find itself discussing: the norm on assisted suicide adopted by the Tuscany Region, a measure that – at least for citizens of that region – fills a normative void denounced by a recent ruling of the Constitutional Court, but on which the Meloni Government does not seem in a condition to intervene by adopting a law valid throughout the national territory.
&nbsp;
Yet, on this theme, Italians seem to have quite clear ideas: more than 70% is favorable both to a law on assisted suicide and – similar but substantially different issue – to decriminalize the practice of euthanasia. What strikes, in data, is not only the entity of the majority of Italians in favor of these practices, but also the transversality of these positions: also among the voters of the center-right, in fact, the percentage of favors is much greater than that of the contrary, in this contradicting the official position of the parties (especially FDI and League) within which, to be true, there are positions dissident like that of the President of Veneto Luca Zaia. If the theme takes on national significance, it is likely that it will be transmuted into a potentially more harmful subject for majority parties than for opposition parties.
